ce"}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASsibCeZf", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 41, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8657813, "raw_content": "One of the reasons gold is such a useful basis for economics is because it is famously stable, convertible, desirable, and value-holding. Gold has never been worth nothing, and it has been used as a system of demonstrating real wealth worldwide for nearly the entire history of our species. You can basically hold any other measure of value up against gold, and gold acts as a very reliable metric to judge what it's really worth against it.\n\nIn 1976, gold was $124 an ounce and the average American annual wage was about $9,200. In 2026, the average income is about $83,000 a year, and gold is about $4450 an ounce.\n\nIt's not just inflation, or housing prices, or the price of eggs or gas. Everything goes up, but not everything goes up *equally*. And the number that has gone up the least is the actual value of your income. Your income in 1976 was nearly 75 ounces of gold. Now it is barely a quarter of that. That's a much bigger problem than whether gas is $4.50 this week but $3.15 six months ago, or whether eggs are $1.50 or $3.50.\n\nWhat this also means, is that whenever someone tells you 'well I just had to save up for....' the fact that you today will have to save up nearly 4 times as much for 4 times longer is automatically baked in. If you dad had to save up for 6 months for something, you have to save for 2 years for the same thing. If he was able to afford some thing with a month's salary, it takes you 4 months for the same thing. It really puts a lot of the 'back in my day' things in stark contrast. \n\nAnd this compounds when you start talking about saving for bigger things. 1 month of saving vs 4 for the same thing is painful. 5 years vs. 20 is a serious problem. 10 years vs. 40 years is straying into 'I could literally die of old age before I can achieve this even under the best circumstances' territory. When someone tells you \"I started saving when I was 20 and by the time I was 30, I was able to afford a....\" means that if you tried to do the same thing, you may very well be in your 60s before you can pull it off. ", "author": "SmiggieBalls", "created": 1780523846085, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Scumbag-reddit", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "50 years ago the average yearly salary was worth 74 ounces of gold. Today it's worth 18.", "last_comment_created": 1780531671129, "content": "<p>One of the reasons gold is such a useful basis for economics is because it is famously stable, convertible, desirable, and value-holding. Gold has never been worth nothing, and it has been used as a system of demonstrating real wealth worldwide for nearly the entire history of our species. You can basically hold any other measure of value up against gold, and gold acts as a very reliable metric to judge what it's really worth against it.</p>\n<p>In 1976, gold was $124 an ounce and the average American annual wage was about $9,200. In 2026, the average income is about $83,000 a year, and gold is about $4450 an ounce.</p>\n<p>It's not just inflation, or housing prices, or the price of eggs or gas. Everything goes up, but not everything goes up <em>equally</em>. And the number that has gone up the least is the actual value of your income. Your income in 1976 was nearly 75 ounces of gold. Now it is barely a quarter of that. That's a much bigger problem than whether gas is $4.50 this week but $3.15 six months ago, or whether eggs are $1.50 or $3.50.</p>\n<p>What this also means, is that whenever someone tells you 'well I just had to save up for....' the fact that you today will have to save up nearly 4 times as much for 4 times longer is automatically baked in. If you dad had to save up for 6 months for something, you have to save for 2 years for the same thing. If he was able to afford some thing with a month's salary, it takes you 4 months for the same thing. It really puts a lot of the 'back in my day' things in stark contrast.</p>\n<p>And this compounds when you start talking about saving for bigger things. 1 month of saving vs 4 for the same thing is painful. 5 years vs. 20 is a serious problem. 10 years vs. 40 years is straying into 'I could literally die of old age before I can achieve this even under the best circumstances' territory. When someone tells you &quot;I started saving when I was 20 and by the time I was 30, I was able to afford a....&quot; means that if you tried to do the same thing, you may very well be in your 60s before you can pull it off.</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 4, "score_up": 41, "is_edited": true, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsibCvYZ", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 37, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "censored", "id": 8657903, "raw_content": "", "author": "Secession2030", "created": 1780525847888, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Secession2030", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "notthebee.com", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "https://media.scored.co/preview/1ASsibCvYZ.png", "removal_source": "", "link": "https://notthebee.com/a